tikzcommands.json — vendored QTikz TikZ command corpus (P94 / D-5)
==================================================================

WHAT
  A categorized, cursor-aware corpus of TikZ commands the editor surfaces on the
  insertion bar AND in the CM6 completion. Each entry is the QTikz native command
  shape:
    name        the command's bare label (Qt `&` menu mnemonics stripped)
    description the completion-popup / status-bar text
    insert      the multi-character string inserted when the command is chosen
    dx, dy      where the editing cursor is placed AFTER insertion, relative to
                the start of the inserted string (the QTikz cursor-placement
                convention; for a single-line insert, dy=0 and dx is the column
                offset within the inserted body). Absent upstream => 0.
    type        the highlighting class (0 plain, 1 command, 2 draw-to, 3 option).

SOURCE
  Derived from QTikz / KtikZ's maintained native command file
  tikzcommands.xml, copied verbatim alongside this file:
    SOURCE REPO: fhackenberger/ktikz  (app/tikzcommands.xml, master)
    URL: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/fhackenberger/ktikz/master/app/tikzcommands.xml
    tikzcommands.xml sha256:
      256f0f4cee7567a1c06945030ebdcfc1da1f335ac0b6815539d3039a39bd355e
  Upstream comment: "This file should only contain the commands and options
  defined in Part III 'TikZ ist kein Zeichenprogramm' in the PGF Manual." It is
  a maintained, categorized corpus — bring it as-is; do not author a snippet list.
  License: QTikz is GPL-2.0 (see the upstream repo's COPYING).

HOW THE JSON IS PRODUCED (a committed converter — interop reshaping only)
  convert-tikzcommands.py (in this dir, stdlib only) reads tikzcommands.xml and
  flattens its `<section>`-grouped `<item>` elements into a JSON array of
  `{name, description, insert, dx, dy, type}` objects — the SAME shape the app
  consumes and the SAME shape the P94/p103 fixture DB uses. The reshaping is a
  pure transcription of the native XML; no command list is authored and no field
  is invented. The only transforms applied are EXACTLY QTikz's own
  (tikzcommandinserter.cpp), so the stored corpus is the literal text QTikz
  inserts:
    - strip the Qt `&` menu mnemonic from `name`/`description` (an `&&` is a
      literal `&`);
    - `restoreNewLines`: a standalone `\n` (not preceded by a backslash, so a
      `\\node` is untouched) becomes a real newline;
    - then `\\` -> `\` collapse, applied AFTER restoreNewLines (QTikz's order);
    - an item with no `name` falls back to its `description` (QTikz's menu
      fallback). Items with no `insert`/`type`, and `<separator/>`/`<section>`
      grouping, carry no command and fail loud / are skipped respectively.
  Reproduce: from this directory, `python3 convert-tikzcommands.py` (rewrites
  tikzcommands.json from tikzcommands.xml). Re-run after refreshing the XML.

HOW THE APP CONSUMES IT
  The corpus is config-owned (no hardcoded command list in the app). Point the
  editor config at this JSON file:

    [editor]
    tikz_commands = "<abs path to this tikzcommands.json>"

  The path is validated to exist at config-load time (ExistingFile in config.rs);
  a config pointing at a missing/non-file path is a hard load error. The editor
  (src/lib/editor/tikz-commands.ts) reads and parses it into the command list and
  builds TWO views of the SAME corpus: the insertion-bar tikz palette (the command
  names) AND a composable CM6 completion source (PUSHED onto the app completion
  registry, composing with the LaTeX/snippet/citation sources — never overriding,
  the P51 lesson). Choosing a command inserts its `insert` body with the cursor
  placed at the declared `dx`/`dy` offset, reusing the shared snippet `$0`-tabstop
  mechanism (src/lib/editor/snippets.ts runSnippet). Pointing the key at a
  different DB surfaces that DB's commands instead — the data-driven property the
  P94 obligation pins. A malformed/unreadable DB raises a visible toastError,
  never a silently-empty palette. The P94 PROOF (p103-tikzcommands-db.spec.ts)
  uses its own committed fixture DBs (tests/proof/fixtures/tikz-commands/) for
  determinism.
